    • Constructor Detail

      • Argument

        public Argument()
        This is the default constructor. If the user provides no name and no description for the argument those values are left blank and the type is defaulted to String. For example: new Argument().

      • Argument

        public Argument(java.lang.String n)
        In this constructor the user specifies the name of the argument but no description. The type is defaulted to String as well. This is done by typing something like this: new Argument("length")
        Parameters:
        n - the name of the argument.

      • Argument

        public Argument(java.lang.String n,
                java.lang.String d)
        In this constructor the user specifies the name and description of the argument. However, the type is defaulted to String. This is done by typing something like this: new Argument("length", "the length of the shape").
        Parameters:
        n - the name of the argument.
        d - the description of the argument.

      • Argument

        public Argument(java.lang.String n,
                java.lang.String d,
                Argument.Type t)
        In this constructor the user specifies the name, description, and type of argument. The value of the argument is set to null until the user assigns a value later on in the program. This is called by the addArg method in ArgumentParser. Usage: new Argument("length", "the length of the shape", Argument.Type.INT).
        Parameters:
        n - the name of the argument.
        d - the description of the argument.
        t - the type of argument.

    • Method Detail

      • setValue

        public void setValue(java.lang.String v)
        This method is called in the parse methods when the user provides a value for an argument.
        Parameters:
        v - the value to be assigned to an argument.

      • getName

        public java.lang.String getName()
        This method returns the name of an argument. Is used for things such as printing out exception messages.
        Returns:
        the name of an argument.

      • setDescription

        public void setDescription(java.lang.String d)
        This method sets the description of an argument. Typically this is never used by the user. Usage example: Argument s = new Argument("length"); s.setDescription("the length");
        Parameters:
        d - the description of the argument.

      • getDescription

        public java.lang.String getDescription()
        This method is used to return the description of an argument. Can be used for things such as exception messages.
        Returns:
        the description of the argument.

      • getValue

        public java.lang.String getValue()
        This method is used to return the value of an argument. This is called in the parser methods in ArgumentParser.
        Returns:
        the value of an argument.

      • getNameAndDescription

        public java.lang.String getNameAndDescription()
        This method is used to return the name and description of various arguments. Typically this method is called to help generate exception messages.
        Returns:
        a string containting the name and description of an argument.

      • getArgType

        public Argument.Type getArgType()
        This method returns the type of argument. This is mostly used for generating certain messages.
        Returns:
        the argument type.

      • getArgTypeAsString

        public java.lang.String getArgTypeAsString()
        This method returns a the type an argument is as a string. This method is used by the stringToXML methods in PosArg and NamedArg, which is used for the save method in the XMLTools class.
        Returns:
        a string showing the type of object an argument is.

      • equals

        public boolean equals(java.lang.Object o)
        This method checks to see if an object is an instance of the Argument class. It is rarely used but can be called by saying: if(Argument.equals("length")) for example.
        Overrides:
        equals in class java.lang.Object
        Returns:
        whether an object is an argument.

      • stringToXML

        public java.lang.String stringToXML()
        This method returns part of the contents of an XML file to be written. This method is called in the save method of the XMLTools class.
        Returns:
        a string that has part of a XML file to be written.
